Assignment 9 - K-means

Author

Aytan Pirverdiyeva

1 Goal of this assignment

The goal of this assignment is for you to explore the k-means algorithm learned in class.

In specific, you will be asked to:
- Use a different number of k than what we did in class,
- Validate the results of the new model, and
- Compare your results with those found in class

2 Instructions

You will first need to watch (and code along with) the following k-means video:

  • k-means lab: https://youtu.be/GFgMp5tYiMU?si=CI0E-2r-cYZLGVL1 (start from beginning of video, watch till the 01:10)
  • The partial script for the video above is in our GitHub repository, 04-classcode, 03-25_multivar_kmeans_partial.qmd. Move the script mentioned above into the code subfolder of your 10_multivar project

AFTER watching the video and developing the code in class, then start working on this HW assignment (instructions below):

  • Move this script into the code subfolder of your 10_multivar project
  • On this script, fill your name under the title section of the YAML
  • Go back to the class k-means script, choose a different number of k than what we did in class, and run it.

4.4 3. Using the fviz_cluster() function, import here the original plot with k=4 did in class, and the new one with the number of k you selected for this exercise. How do they visually compare? Which one seems to be a better choice, and why?

##Answer: ### Although there was a noticeable overlap between Cluster 1 (red) and Cluster 4 (purple) in the lower-middle region, the original figure with k = 4 demonstrated a respectable separation between the main clusters. This made interpretation a little more difficult, particularly in the vicinity of the center. ###The k = 5 layout, on the other hand, divided that congested region into more precise groups, improving visual separation. By establishing a unique cluster for the core region, the fifth cluster made it easier to separate patterns that had previously been grouped together.Despite the new clusterâs tiny size (only 16 observations), it was simpler to understand the general structure and the distinctions across clusters. ###Since it minimizes overlap and captures more detail without being overly complicated, I think k = 5 provides a better clustering approach for this dataset.

Code 
fviz_cluster(mod_km5,
             data = weather_norm)
Code 
fviz_cluster(mod_km4,
             data = weather_norm)
